<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription xmi:version="2.0" xmlns:xmi="http://www.omg.org/XMI" xmlns:org.eclipse.epf.uma="http://www.eclipse.org/epf/uma/1.0.6/uma.ecore" xmlns:epf="http://www.eclipse.org/epf" epf:version="1.5.1" xmlns:rmc="http://www.ibm.com/rmc" rmc:version="7.5.1" xmi:id="-hMH8FZFX2hsBPxVEJ5Vd_w" name="provide_ent_tool_adopt_supp,_a-3KEEmIEd-H4JlF2fadEg" guid="-hMH8FZFX2hsBPxVEJ5Vd_w" changeDate="2010-11-15T11:58:45.640-0800" version="7.5.0">
  <mainDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Tools are only as good as the process they automate, and they are useful only in the hands of skilled people. Just as&#xD;
    putting power tools in the hands of inexperienced users can hurt them, putting software automation tools in&#xD;
    inexperienced hands will not only keep a project from achieving the desired results, but may also cause harm.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The most effective method for introducing change is to tie improvement efforts directly to the work being performed.&#xD;
    Use project and iteration planning to drive the introduction of new tools, configurations,&amp;nbsp;and techniques, just&#xD;
    ahead of when they should&amp;nbsp;be applied. Jump-start changes and facilitate skills transfer through a series of&#xD;
    focused workshops followed by hands-on mentoring.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Guide and advise the project team so that they can apply&amp;nbsp;the tools&amp;nbsp;appropriately:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Lead workshops, create usage models, and review artifacts created using the tool configurations&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Help the project manager create and execute plans and manage issues&amp;nbsp;and risks.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Introduce the &quot;right&quot; amount of&amp;nbsp;change so as to not to slow down the project's progress:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div&#xD;
        style=&quot;mso-line-spacing: '100 25 15'; mso-margin-left-alt: 526; mso-text-indent-alt: 326; mso-char-wrap: 1; mso-kinsoku-overflow: 1&quot;&#xD;
         class=&quot;O1&quot;>&#xD;
            Follow &quot;minimal but sufficient principle.&quot;&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div&#xD;
        style=&quot;mso-line-spacing: '100 25 15'; mso-margin-left-alt: 526; mso-text-indent-alt: 326; mso-char-wrap: 1; mso-kinsoku-overflow: 1&quot;&#xD;
         class=&quot;O1&quot;>&#xD;
            Mentoring is about &quot;leading change.&quot;&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div&#xD;
        style=&quot;mso-line-spacing: '100 25 15'; mso-margin-left-alt: 526; mso-text-indent-alt: 326; mso-char-wrap: 1; mso-kinsoku-overflow: 1&quot;&#xD;
         class=&quot;O1&quot;>&#xD;
            The goal is to make progress in the project, not enforcing tool ceremony.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div&#xD;
        style=&quot;mso-line-spacing: '100 25 15'; mso-margin-left-alt: 526; mso-text-indent-alt: 326; mso-char-wrap: 1; mso-kinsoku-overflow: 1&quot;&#xD;
         class=&quot;O1&quot;>&#xD;
            Mentoring is not about theoretical discussion of the features of the tool.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        &lt;div&#xD;
        style=&quot;mso-line-spacing: '100 25 15'; mso-margin-left-alt: 526; mso-text-indent-alt: 326; mso-char-wrap: 1; mso-kinsoku-overflow: 1&quot;&#xD;
         class=&quot;O1&quot;>&#xD;
            Mentoring is not about religious battles between different usage models.&#xD;
        &lt;/div>&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p&#xD;
style=&quot;mso-line-spacing: '100 25 15'; mso-margin-left-alt: 526; mso-text-indent-alt: 326; mso-char-wrap: 1; mso-kinsoku-overflow: 1&quot;&#xD;
 class=&quot;O1&quot;>&#xD;
    A key part of the mentoring&amp;nbsp;effort is&amp;nbsp;providing feedback and lessons learned in order to improve&amp;nbsp;the&#xD;
    tool configurations and usage models.&#xD;
&lt;/p></mainDescription>
  <keyConsiderations>&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Mentoring is successful if the project team shows improved project performance (e.g. iterations on time, on budget,&#xD;
        fewer issues, fewer risks, lower defect rate).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A good mentor must be able to adjust the&amp;nbsp;Mentoring Action Plan&amp;nbsp;&quot;on the fly&quot; based on the needs of the&#xD;
        project.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        A project team may need multiple mentors in different areas.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        The mentoring relationship must be terminated if the project team is not making desired progress. The Center of&#xD;
        Capability must investigate and determine the root cause. Either the mentor or the project team (or a specific&#xD;
        role) or an&amp;nbsp;ineffective tool configuration&amp;nbsp;could be primarily responsible for the failure.&lt;br />&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></keyConsiderations>
  <sections xmi:id="_gayMwJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA" name="Conduct mentoring kick-off workshop" guid="_gayMwJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    During the kick-off session the project team&amp;nbsp;and mentor&amp;nbsp;discuss and determine:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        mentoring objectives for the project team&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        roles&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        training that the project teams need&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    In this workshop the&amp;nbsp;mentor learns the context and background of the project.&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_kAHUsJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA" name="Create deployment and action plan for the project" guid="_kAHUsJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Create a simple plan of tool deployment and adoption activities for the project. This plan should take the team's&#xD;
    project plan into consideration. A&amp;nbsp;key objective is that the&amp;nbsp;deployment&amp;nbsp;and adoption activities should&#xD;
    have minimal to no negative impact to the project. The scope of mentoring may vary depending on the&#xD;
    enterprise&amp;nbsp;tool adoption schedule, the specific project and project team.&amp;nbsp;&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Assess the current state of capability of the project team (their strengths and weaknesses) in various tool aspects and&#xD;
    related processes, and then determine where to focus first.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Tool adoption must take place in an iterative, incremental and evolutionary manner.&amp;nbsp;Plan mentoring activities and&#xD;
    deployment of the tools with this in mind.&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_t_OpMJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA" name="Provide training sessions in tool areas" guid="_t_OpMJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA">
    <sectionDescription>Conduct training sessions to introduce the team to key concepts and capabilities of the tool. This is only a precursor, not&#xD;
a replacement, for the learning that takes place through execution on the project.&lt;br /></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_4ypIcJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA" name="Conduct mentoring sessions" guid="_4ypIcJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Conduct&amp;nbsp;regular mentoring sessions with the team. There must be at least one session per week (on-site or&#xD;
        remote).&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Create a clear agenda for each session. Only the relevant roles (e.g. Project Manager, Analyst, Designer)&amp;nbsp;will&#xD;
        attend.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Check what tasks have been completed since the last mentoring sessions. Check the status of issues, risks and&#xD;
        defects. Check what tasks/activities need to be completed this week.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        Discuss and point to concepts, guidelines, and examples.&amp;nbsp; Artifact examples are always very helpful for&#xD;
        project teams.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        At the end of&amp;nbsp;each mentoring session, review the task list that needs to be completed by the project team by&#xD;
        the next mentoring session.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    For guidance on how to plan and schedule for mentoring sessions see &lt;a class=&quot;elementLinkWithType&quot;&#xD;
    href=&quot;./../../practice.bus.adopt_through_execution.base-ibm/guidances/guidelines/plan_mentoring_schedule_A86E89E8.html&quot;&#xD;
    guid=&quot;_pMq0wJUEEd-0-OAVgoUtMw&quot;>Guideline: Plan the Mentoring Schedule&lt;/a>.&#xD;
&lt;/p></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_7248kJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA" name="Review the artifacts created by the project team using the tool" guid="_7248kJUiEd-M6uvIwyKefA">
    <sectionDescription>As a project progresses,&amp;nbsp; document the&amp;nbsp;tool capabilities the team applied during each iteration. This enables the&#xD;
organization to collect experiences across projects. It also enables teams&amp;nbsp;to not only&amp;nbsp;apply configuration&#xD;
changes in subsequent iterations of current projects, but also to use them as the basis for new projects. This results in&#xD;
enterprise tool configurations that&amp;nbsp;are grounded in practical experience and can grow to support the organization's&#xD;
specific needs. Instead of being a theoretical exercise,&amp;nbsp;tool configurations&amp;nbsp;emerge from the experience of&#xD;
solving problems and delivering results.</sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_IUshEJUjEd-M6uvIwyKefA" name="Identify potential new mentors" guid="_IUshEJUjEd-M6uvIwyKefA">
    <sectionDescription>Identify team members who are good candidates to mentor other teams based on what they learned&amp;nbsp;using the tool on this&#xD;
project.</sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <sections xmi:id="_MzPwAJUjEd-M6uvIwyKefA" name="Collect measurements and lessons learned" guid="_MzPwAJUjEd-M6uvIwyKefA">
    <sectionDescription>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Provide feedback about the team's adoption of the tool. These lessons learned provide critical feedback&amp;nbsp;that&#xD;
    enables&amp;nbsp;continuous improvement of the enterprise tool configurations. Examples of helpful feedback to collect&#xD;
    throughout the mentoring project&amp;nbsp;include:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        incompatibilities between the tool and related processes&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        impact of&amp;nbsp;tool usage&amp;nbsp;to the project (positive and negative impacts)&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Collect the following feedback from the project team:&#xD;
&lt;/p>&#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        effectiveness of the tool&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        effectiveness of training sessions&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        effectiveness of mentoring sessions&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul></sectionDescription>
  </sections>
  <purpose>&lt;p>&#xD;
    Mentoring accelerates adoption of&amp;nbsp;enterprise tools&amp;nbsp;by a project team. Mentors play a catalytic role in making&#xD;
    change successful. People will accept change if they feel confident of the outcome. Good mentors not only transfer&#xD;
    skills but also instill confidence.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:TaskDescription>
